olinguistic adaptation meant that the usual barriers to communication between the hearing and the Deaf, which so isolate many Deaf people today, did not exist.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aDeafzMassachusettszMartha's VineyardxHistory. 0aDeafnessxGenetic aspects. 0aSign language. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Linguistics / Sociolinguistics.2bisacsh1 aWhiting, John W. M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHUP eBook Package Archive 1893-1999z978311044221240uhttps://doi.org/10.4159/9780674037953?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780674037953423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780674037953/original  a978-3-11-044221-2  HUP eBook Package Archive 1893-1999c1893d1999  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles